2":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Worthington, Wigan, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, England","Ormskirk, West Lancashire, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Worthington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire, Cheshire, and Staffordshire): habitational name from any of the places in Lancashire and Leicestershire named Worthington. The placenames probably derive from an Old English personal name <i>Weorth</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","History: Nicholas Worthington emigrated from England to Old Saybrook, CT, <i>c.</i> 1650."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Worthington was born in 1220, in Worthington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Knight Thomas de Worthington, was 37 and his mother, Alice of England, was 45. He married Elene De Charnock in 1240, in Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1282, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Surnud","1238–1297":"1238–1297","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1246–1297":"1246–1297","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1238":"1238","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1246":"1246","1222":"1222","Abt 1242":"umbes 1242","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1297":"1297","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1282":"1282","1183":"1183","Worthington, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Worthington, Wigan, Lancashire, England":"Worthington, Lancashire, England","Ormskirk, West Lancashire, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Ormskirk, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1220–1282":"1220–1282","1222–Male":"1222–Kuollut","1238–1297":"1238–1297","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1246–1297":"1246–1297","1183–1242":"1183–1242","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1238":"